description.@value: I couldn't help but think of LS's piece while reading about the rigid rules regarding movement at many urban charter schools described in this piece: http://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2014/12/how-strict-is-too-strict/382228/?single_page=true. For example, kids can be disciplined for failing to walk silently in the hallways while following lines taped to the floor. From the Atlantic piece: "Some go further, arguing that those taped lines point the way to prison rather than to college—that the harsh discipline is a civil-rights abomination, destined to push too many kids out of school and into trouble with the law. For the families involved, particularly the students, the story is more complicated. Many of them come to appreciate the intense structure, but only if they also come to trust the mostly young educators who enforce it. As school leaders in New Orleans are discovering, forging that trust is far harder than teaching someone to say thank you and toe an orange line."

title.@value: More yoga/capoeira/movement spaces in public space

description.@value:
I was flying through the San Francisco airport a few weeks ago and I noticed that they had a yoga room in addition to the usual ecumenical prayer room in the airport. What a great idea to cultivate the body as well as the soul! 

I wish that more airports, public spaces, work places and the like would set aside a little bit of space like this for mind/body movement practices of this kind.

title.@value: How Ford's Focus was designed with 'aging suits'

description.@value:
I'd not heard it called body-storming before, but increasing empathy with those you are thinking about reaching/changing/designing for makes perfect sense. 

Ford used aging suits to dress up their designers on the Focus - it worked for them!

Schools in Japan also gave students more time in between classes to move about. They had several breaks throughout the day. Classrooms tended to also be very open to the outdoors with lots of windows which gave schools a sense of openness. All these help allow for movement. Can public spaces and offices spaces reflect this?

title.@value: Or even just allowing for movement. When I taught english in Japan, I noticed how in the hallways be

description.@value: tween classes students were allowed to be very free. To run around, visit other classrooms. This contrasted greatly, how still they were supposed to be during the lessons. I remember going to school while growing up in Ohio and then later visiting schools in NYC, how students were not allowed to walk freely in the hallways even in between classes. You could pretty much walk to another classroom and that was it. The freedom of movement Japanese children had from even a young age is in stark contrast to American children who are discouraged from 'running around'. American children move from one classroom 'box' to another. Once, I saw the difference in Japan, I was really bothered by the lack of movement we allow our children and ourselves as we grow into adults. I don't have answers on how to fix this but having more public space for it is a start. Though, I think it goes deeper and we need to address how we allow ourselves to move.

Love bodystorming! Haven't done this in a few years but I think it goes right along with rapid prototyping. It really helps everyone understand and feel a user experience. It also gets you out of your head and into the real world.
Also, I would suggest trying improv classes. This also helps you get your mind and body working.
